    <h1>GEC Security and Trust</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <p>Security is a perspective of the IDS Reference Architecture Mode=
l that has implications in all its different layers. Some documentation abo=
ut the implementation of security levels in a connector is available at&nbs=
p;<a href=3D"https://www.ids.isst.fraunhofer.de/confluence/display/ID/Secur=
ity+Architecture" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">IDS Security (ID=
S Lab)</a>. In GEC different levels of security can be supported by connect=
ors in all these aspects</p>
<ol>
<li>Remote Attestation</li>
<li>Secure communication&nbsp;</li>
<li>Identity management&nbsp; and authentication</li>
<li>Authorization and Usage control</li>
</ol>
<p>In addition, other aspects to take into account are</p>
<ul>
<li>Secure storage (encryption of stored data)</li>
<li>Provenance (what is the source of the data ?)</li>
</ul>
<h1 id=3D"GECSecurityandTrust-RemoteAttestation">Remote Attestation</h1>
<p>The hardware used for processing, storage or communication can mount a s=
pecial chip, such as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trusted_Pla=
tform_Module" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">Trusted Platform Mod=
ule (</a><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trusted_Platform_Module" =
class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">TPM</a><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Trusted_Platform_Module" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofol=
low">)</a>, with a certificate released by its manufacturer to support disk=
 encryption, hardware integrity. The software running in a connector as app=
 must come from a trusted party, its integrity must be assessed and it shou=
ld run in a isolated environment, e.g. a container, so that it will not be =
able to access memory or file system allocated to other processes.</p>
<h1 id=3D"GECSecurityandTrust-SecureCommunication">Secure Communication</h1=
>
<p>Secure communication relies on the use of the HTTPS protocol. It support=
s confidentiality and message integrity via&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Transport_Layer_Security" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nof=
ollow">TLS</a>,&nbsp;a protocol based on the Public Key Infrastructure (PKI=
).&nbsp;</p>
<h1 id=3D"GECSecurityandTrust-IdentityManagementandAuthentication">Identity=
 Management and Authentication</h1>
<p>The IDS association has a body that is in charge of delivering certifica=
tes or assigning the task to sub-authorities. An organization that is trust=
ed by the IDS can create certificates for its own connectors.&nbsp;The pref=
erred way of handling the authentication for all the connectors and compone=
nts of the IDS ecosystem is to use a single sign-on system for all of them.=
 There are different frameworks that can be used for authentication, one is=
 the <span style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0=
);">Dynamic Attribute Provisioning Service (</span></span>DAPS), developed =
by Fraunhofer AISEC, and another one is <a href=3D"https://www.keycloak.org=
/index.html" style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D"external-link" rel=
=3D"nofollow">Keycloak</a>. They both are based on the OAuth2.0 protocol an=
d use <a href=3D"https://jwt.io/" style=3D"letter-spacing: 0.0px;" class=3D=
"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">JSON Web Tokens (JWT)</a> to authenticate =
data consumers, data providers and other participants.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<h2 id=3D"GECSecurityandTrust-DynamicAttributeProvisioningService"><span st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Dynamic Attribute Provisioning Service</span></h=
2>
<p>The DAPS is loaded with connectors' certificate with their public keys p=
lus attributes about the organization that manages or owns the connector.</=
p>
<h2 id=3D"GECSecurityandTrust-Keycloak"><span style=3D"color: rgb(85,85,85)=
;">Keycloak</span></h2>
<p>Keycloak is an open source framework for authentication and authorizatio=
n management. It is based on the OAuth2.0 protocol. With Keycloak a consume=
r connector that wants to fetch a static resource, e.g. a file, can send an=
 ArtifactRequestMessage to a data provider with a JWT token that has been p=
reviously obtained from Keycloak. The provider connector verify the token s=
ending a message to Keycloak. If the token is valid, i.e. the sender is kno=
wn and the token is not expired, the provider will process the request and,=
 if the consumer is authorized to access the resources, it will be sent to =
it in the response.</p>
<h1 id=3D"GECSecurityandTrust-AuthorizationandUsageControl">Authorization a=
nd Usage Control</h1>
<p>Authorization can be implemented as local rules in the connector, e.g. A=
ccess Control List, or by centralized systems, e.g. by roles set on Keycloa=
k.</p>
<h1 id=3D"GECSecurityandTrust-Infrastructure">Infrastructure</h1>
<p>A list of infrastructure technologies for each of the security perspecti=
ves&nbsp;</p>
<ol>
<li>AISEC Trusted 3rd Party (RAT Repository)</li>
<li>Let's Encrypt or IDS Certificates</li>
<li>DAPS / Keycloak</li>
<li>Access Control List / LUCON</li>
</ol>
